			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Partial Loading of Repository-Based Models through Static Analysis</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SorourJahanbin.html">Sorour Jahanbin</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/SimosGerasimou.html">Simos Gerasimou</a>, <a href="../profile/GersonSunyé.html">Gerson Sunyé</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567535">10.1145/3567512.3567535</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagM">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> The main goal is improving scalability (time/memory) of model management via partial loading.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It uses static analysis of model management programs to determine what to load.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It generates graph-database (Cypher) queries that map model-management needs to repository retrieval.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The work targets model management/transformation/validation languages and their execution engines.
</li></ul></li></ul>
